{"id":"2108.06408","submitter":"Frederick Law","authors":"Frederick Law, Antoine Cerfon, Benjamin Peherstorfer","title":"Accelerating the estimation of energetic particle confinement statistics\n  in stellarators using multifidelity Monte Carlo","comments":"18 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1741-4326/ac4777","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.plasm-ph cs.NA math.NA physics.comp-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  In the design of stellarators, energetic particle confinement is a critical\npoint of concern which remains challenging to study from a numerical point of\nview. Standard Monte Carlo analyses are highly expensive because a large number\nof particle trajectories need to be integrated over long time scales, and small\ntime steps must be taken to accurately capture the features of the wide variety\nof trajectories. Even when they are based on guiding center trajectories, as\nopposed to full-orbit trajectories, these standard Monte Carlo studies are too\nexpensive to be included in most stellarator optimization codes. We present the\nfirst multifidelity Monte Carlo scheme for accelerating the estimation of\nenergetic particle confinement in stellarators. Our approach relies on a\ntwo-level hierarchy, in which a guiding center model serves as the\nhigh-fidelity model, and a data-driven linear interpolant is leveraged as the\nlow-fidelity surrogate model. We apply multifidelity Monte Carlo to the study\nof energetic particle confinement in a 4-period quasi-helically symmetric\nstellarator, assessing various metrics of confinement. Stemming from the very\nhigh computational efficiency of our surrogate model as well as its sufficient\ncorrelation to the high-fidelity model, we obtain speedups of up to 10 with\nmultifidelity Monte Carlo compared to standard Monte Carlo.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 13 Aug 2021 21:30:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-05-18"}
